04947nam a22007815i 9780231547109DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019006025  a97802315471097 a10.7312/more177362doi  a(DE-B1597)541726  a(OCoLC)1125113378  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aRC341b.M727 2019 4aRC341b.M727 2020 7aMED0570002bisacsh04a612.8/2332231 aMoreno, Jonathan D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Brain in Context :bA Pragmatic Guide to Neuroscience /cJonathan D. Moreno, Jay Schulkin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. ELECTRIFYING -- t2. CONSTRUCTING -- t3. EVOLVING -- t4. IMAGING -- t5. ENGINEERING -- t6. SECURING -- t7. HEALING -- t8. SOCIALIZING -- tNOT THE LAST WORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe human brain is the most complex object in the known universe. The field of neuroscience has made remarkable strides in recent years in understanding aspects of the brain, yet we still struggle with seemingly fundamental questions about how the brain works. What lessons can we learn from neuroscience’s successes and failures? What kinds of questions can neuroscience answer, and what will remain out of reach?In The Brain in Context, the bioethicist Jonathan D. Moreno and the neuroscientist Jay Schulkin provide an accessible and thought-provoking account of the evolution of neuroscience and the neuroscience of evolution. They emphasize that the brain is not an isolated organ—it extends into every part of the body and every aspect of human life. Understanding the brain requires studying the environmental, biological, chemical, genetic, and social factors that continue to shape it. Moreno and Schulkin describe today’s transformative devices, theories, and methods, including technologies like fMRI and optogenetics as well as massive whole-brain activity maps and the attempt to create a digital simulation of the brain. They show how theorizing about the brain and experimenting with it often go hand in hand, and they raise cautions about unintended consequences of technological interventions. The Brain in Context is a stimulating and even-handed assessment of the scope and limits of what we know about how we think.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNeurosciencesvPopular works. 0aNeurotechnology (Bioengineering)vPopular works. 0aNeurotechnology (Bioengineering). 7aMEDICAL / Neuroscience.2bisacsh1 aSchulkin, Jay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019 Englishz978311061053608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019z9783110606386oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/more1773640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231547109423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231547109/original  a978-3-11-061053-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-071097-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  